The pipe operator |&gt;


# Data prep
cars |&gt; 
  mutate(time = dist / speed) |&gt; 
  arrange(-time) |&gt; 
  slice(1)


  speed dist     time
1    14   80 5.714286





Often we will save the output of such a chain using the assignment operator &lt;-


# Data prep
longestTime &lt;- cars |&gt;
  mutate(time = dist / speed) |&gt; 
  arrange(-time) |&gt; 
  slice(1)

longestTime


  speed dist     time
1    14   80 5.714286

Factors in R
We can group_by() this new variable, then use summarise() to calculate the average speed for each group.


# Create a new variable
cars |&gt; 
  mutate(
    class = case_when(
      speed &lt;= 4 ~ "slow", 
      speed &lt;= 10 ~ "average", 
      .default = "fast"
    )) |&gt; 
  group_by(class) |&gt;  
  summarise(
    mean = mean(speed)
  ) 


# A tibble: 3 Ã— 2
  class    mean
  &lt;chr&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;
1 average  8.71
2 fast    17.1 
3 slow     4   




Notice the ordering of the output! This is because the new class variable is a character vector.
